    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-03-19T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-03-18T18:30:00-05:00" n="204"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d204">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857/423</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Cork</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Frost</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cork</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >Queenstown</hi>)</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1917-03-19T19:00:00-05:00"
                            notBefore="1917-03-18T23:30:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">undated</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 19, 1917, 7
                        p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>British tanker <hi rend="italic">Lucilline</hi>, New York bound Calais with
                    naphtha, 2,424 tons register, 35 complement, was struck by torpedo without
                    warning at 2 a.m., March 13, about 40 miles west Bull Light. One man killed by
                    explosion and latter wrecked one lifeboat, necessitating use of small gig which
                    capsized [with?] 12 men, 1 man died fumes naphtha. Survivors saved by admiralty
                    escort which towed <hi rend="italic">Lucilline</hi>, bringing her shore two days
                    later. <hi rend="italic">Lucilline</hi> had neither wireless nor gun. Made no
                    attempt escape but was under escort. Submarine not seen by <hi rend="italic"
                        >Lucilline’s</hi> crew but by escort. Weather was moderate sea, light
                    breeze, moonlight alternating black clouds. Sole American, D. W. Townsend,
                    seaman, 1122 Columbia Street, Seattle, survives uninjured. Have joint affidavit
                    Townsend and third officer. This to Ambassador, Consul General.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Frost</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
